# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: open-addressing-probing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:open-addressing-probing/2-choice-hashing] 2-choice hashing utilizes two hash functions *h*1(*x*) and *h*2(*x*).
[src:open-addressing-probing/2-choice-hashing] The two hash functions should be independent and have no correlation to each other.
[src:open-addressing-probing/2-choice-hashing] Having two hash functions allows any key *x* to have up to two potential locations to be stored based on the values of the respective outputs, *h*1(*x*) and *h*2(*x*).
[src:open-addressing-probing/2-choice-hashing] Although there are two hash functions, there is only one table; both hash functions map to locations on that table.
[src:open-addressing-probing/2-choice-hashing] The most important functions of the hashing implementation in this case are insertion and search.
[src:open-addressing-probing/2-choice-hashing] As is true with all hash tables, the performance is based on the largest bucket.
[src:open-addressing-probing/2-choice-hashing] Although there are instances where bucket sizes happen to be large based on the values and the hash functions used, this is rare.
[src:open-addressing-probing/2-choice-hashing] Having two hash functions and, therefore, two possible locations for any one value, makes the possibility of large buckets even more unlikely to happen.
[src:open-addressing-probing/2-choice-hashing] The expected bucket size while using 2-choice hashing is: *θ*(log(log(*n*))).
[src:open-addressing-probing/2-choice-hashing] This improvement is due to the randomized concept known as The Power of Two Choices.
[src:open-addressing-probing/2-choice-hashing] Using two hash functions offers substantial benefits over a single hash function.
[src:open-addressing-probing/2-choice-hashing] Some people recommend a type of 2-choice hashing called two-way skewed-associative cache in some CPU caches.
[src:open-addressing-probing/2-choice-hashing] 2-left hashing—using two hash tables of equal size *n*/2, and asymmetrically resolving ties by putting the key in the left hash table—has fewer collisions and therefore better performance than 2-choice hashing with one large hash table of size *n*.
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] The double hashing technique uses one hash value as an index into the table and then repeatedly steps forward an interval until the desired value is located, an empty location is reached, or the entire table has been searched; but this interval is set by a second, independent hash function.
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] Unlike the alternative collision-resolution methods of linear probing and quadratic probing, the interval depends on the data, so that values mapping to the same location have different bucket sequences; this minimizes repeated collisions and the effects of clustering.
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] Generally, $h_{1}$ and $h_{2}$ are selected from a set of universal hash functions; $h_{1}$ is selected to have a range of $\{0,|T|-1\}$ and $h_{2}$ to have a range of $\{1,|T|-1\}$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] Double hashing approximates a random distribution; more precisely, pair-wise independent hash functions yield a probability of $(n/|T|)^{2}$ that any pair of keys will follow the same bucket sequence.
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] All $h_{2}(x)$ should be *relatively prime* to $|T|$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] Otherwise the number of indices probed over *k* items would be $\min(k,|T|/h_{2}(x))$ , which could be as small as 2.
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] It should cycle through the whole table.
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] It should be pair-wise independent of $h_{1}(x)$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] The distribution characteristics of $h_{2}$ are irrelevant.
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] It is analogous to a random-number generator.
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] Suppose one selects two hash functions $h_{1}$ and $h_{2}$ and inserts $\alpha |T|$ elements into a hash table with $|T|$ slots.
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] Given this setup, theoretical analyses seek to determine the time needed to perform an additional insertion (or, equivalently, the time needed to perform an unsuccessful search).
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] Guibas and Szemerédi proved in 1978 that, if $h_{1}$ and $h_{2}$ are uniformly random, and $\alpha <0.319$ , then the expected time is $O(1)$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] Subsequent work by Lueker and Molodowitch proved a bound of $1/(1-\alpha )$ for any $\alpha$ , and established that the behavior of the hash table can be directly coupled to that of a standard random-probing based solution.
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] Much more recently, in 2007, Bradford and Katehakis showed that even using universal hash functions, rather than fully random ones, suffices to get a $1/(1-\alpha )$ bound.
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] Like all other forms of open addressing, double hashing becomes linear as the hash table approaches maximum capacity.
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] The usual heuristic is to limit the table loading to 75% of capacity.
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] Eventually, rehashing to a larger size will be necessary, as with all other open addressing schemes.
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] This makes a collision twice as likely as the hoped-for $1/|T|^{2}$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] There are additionally a significant number of mostly-overlapping hash sets; if $h_{2}(y)=h_{2}(x)$ and $h_{1}(y)=h_{1}(x)\pm h_{2}(x)$ , then $h(i,y)=h(i\pm 1,x)$ , and comparing additional hash values (expanding the range of i ) is of no help.
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] Adding a third hash as a quadratic term (**triple hashing**) makes the overlap a lot less likely, since equivalent classes now need to be generated by a collaboration of both $h_{2}(x)$ and $h_{3}(x)$ , at a cost of 50% more calculations due to the added hash function.
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] Choices for the factor for this $h_{3}(x)$ include $i^{2}$ and the triangular numbers $i(i\pm 1)/2$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] The added hash function should obey the same requirements as listed above for $h_{2}(x)$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] This kind of construction does not fully remove equivalent sets.
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] Adding a cubic term $i^{3}$ or $(i^{3}-i)/6$ (a tetrahedral number), does solve the problem, a technique known as **enhanced double hashing**.
[src:open-addressing-probing/double-hashing] In addition to rectifying the collision problem, enhanced double hashing also removes double-hashing's numerical restrictions on $h_{2}(x)$ 's properties, allowing a hash function similar in property to (but still independent of) $h_{1}$ to be used.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] In computer science, a **hash table** is a data structure that implements an associative array, also called a **dictionary** or simply **map**; an associative array is an abstract data type that maps keys to values.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] A hash table uses a hash function to compute an *index*, also called a *hash code*, into an array of *buckets* or *slots*, from which the desired value can be found.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] During lookup, the key is hashed and the resulting hash indicates where the corresponding value is stored.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] A map implemented by a hash table is called a **hash map**.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Most hash table designs employ an imperfect hash function.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Hash collisions, where the hash function generates the same index for more than one key, therefore typically must be accommodated in some way.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Common strategies to handle hash collisions include chaining, which stores multiple elements in the same slot using linked lists, and open addressing, which searches for the next available slot according to a probing sequence.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] In a well-dimensioned hash table, the average time complexity for each lookup is independent of the number of elements stored in the table.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Many hash table designs also allow arbitrary insertions and deletions of key–value pairs, at amortized constant average cost per operation.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Hashing is an example of a space–time tradeoff.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] If memory is infinite, the entire key can be used directly as an index to locate its value with a single memory access.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] On the other hand, if infinite time is available, values can be stored without regard for their keys, and a binary search or linear search can be used to retrieve the element.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] In many situations, hash tables turn out to be on average more efficient than search trees or any other table lookup structure.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] For this reason, they are widely used in many kinds of computer software, particularly for associative arrays, database indexing, caches, and sets.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Many programming languages provide built-in hash table structures, such as Python’s dictionaries, Java’s HashMap, C++’s unordered_map, Go maps, which abstract the complexity of hashing from the programmer.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The idea of hashing arose independently in different places.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] In January 1953, Hans Peter Luhn wrote an internal IBM memorandum that used hashing with chaining.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The first example of open addressing was proposed by A.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Around the same time, Gene Amdahl, Elaine M.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] McGraw, Nathaniel Rochester, and Arthur Samuel of IBM Research implemented hashing for the IBM 701 assembler.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Open addressing with linear probing is credited to Amdahl, although Andrey Ershov independently had the same idea.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The term "open addressing" was coined by W.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Wesley Peterson in his article which discusses the problem of search in large files.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The first published work on hashing with chaining is credited to Arnold Dumey, who discussed the idea of using remainder modulo a prime as a hash function.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The word "hashing" was first published in an article by Robert Morris.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] A theoretical analysis of linear probing was submitted originally by Konheim and Weiss.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] An associative array stores a set of (key, value) pairs and allows insertion, deletion, and lookup (search), with the constraint of unique keys.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] In the hash table implementation of associative arrays, an array A of length m is partially filled with n elements, where $m\geq n$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] A key **x** is hashed using a hash function h to compute an index location $A[h(x)]$ in the hash table, where $h(x)<m$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The efficiency of a hash table depends on the load factor, defined as the ratio of the number of stored elements to the number of available slots, with lower load factors generally yielding faster operations.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] At this index, both the key and its associated value are stored.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Storing the key alongside the value ensures that lookups can verify the key at the index to retrieve the correct value, even in the presence of collisions.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Under reasonable assumptions, hash tables have better time complexity bounds on search, delete, and insert operations in comparison to self-balancing binary search trees.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Hash tables are also commonly used to implement sets, by omitting the stored value for each key and merely tracking whether the key is present.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The performance of the hash table deteriorates in relation to the load factor $\alpha$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] In the limit of large m and n , each bucket statistically has a Poisson distribution with expectation $\lambda =\alpha$ for an ideally random hash function.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The software typically ensures that the load factor $\alpha$ remains below a certain constant, $\alpha _{\max }$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Therefore, a common approach is to resize or "rehash" the hash table whenever the load factor $\alpha$ reaches $\alpha _{\max }$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Similarly the table may also be resized if the load factor drops below $\alpha _{\max }/4$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] With separate chaining hash tables, each slot of the bucket array stores a pointer to a list or array of data.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Separate chaining hash tables suffer gradually declining performance as the load factor grows, and no fixed point beyond which resizing is absolutely needed.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] With separate chaining, the value of $\alpha _{\max }$ that gives best performance is typically between 1 and 3.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] With open addressing, each slot of the bucket array holds exactly one item.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Therefore an open-addressed hash table cannot have a load factor greater than 1.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The performance of open addressing becomes very bad when the load factor approaches 1.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Therefore a hash table that uses open addressing *must* be resized or *rehashed* if the load factor $\alpha$ approaches 1.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] With open addressing, acceptable figures of max load factor $\alpha _{\max }$ should range around 0.6 to 0.75.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] A hash function $h:U\rightarrow \{0,...,m-1\}$ maps the universe U of keys to indices or slots within the table, that is, $h(x)\in \{0,...,m-1\}$ for $x\in U$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The conventional implementations of hash functions are based on the *integer universe assumption* that all elements of the table stem from the universe $U=\{0,...,u-1\}$ , where the bit length of u is confined within the word size of a computer architecture.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] A hash function h is said to be perfect for a given set S if it is injective on S , that is, if each element $x\in S$ maps to a different value in ${0,...,m-1}$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] A perfect hash function can be created if all the keys are known ahead of time.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The schemes of hashing used in *integer universe assumption* include hashing by division, hashing by multiplication, universal hashing, dynamic perfect hashing, and static perfect hashing.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] However, hashing by division is the commonly used scheme.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The scheme in hashing by division is as follows: $h(x)\ =\ x\,{\bmod {\,}}m,$ where $h(x)$ is the hash value of $x\in S$ and m is the size of the table.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The scheme in hashing by multiplication is as follows: $h(x)=\lfloor m{\bigl (}(xA){\bmod {1}}{\bigr )}\rfloor$ Where A is a non-integer real-valued constant and m is the size of the table.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] An advantage of the hashing by multiplication is that the m is not critical.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Although any value A produces a hash function, Donald Knuth suggests using the golden ratio.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Commonly a string is used as a key to the hash function.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The third edition of *The C++ Programming Language* describes a simple hash function in which an unsigned integer that is initially zero is repeatedly left shifted one bit and then xor'ed with the integer value of the next character.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] This hash value is then taken modulo the table size.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] If the left shift is not circular, then the string length should be at least eight bits less than the size of the unsigned integer in bits.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Another common way to hash a string to an integer is with a polynomial rolling hash function.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Uniform distribution of the hash values is a fundamental requirement of a hash function.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] A non-uniform distribution increases the number of collisions and the cost of resolving them.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Uniformity is sometimes difficult to ensure by design, but may be evaluated empirically using statistical tests, e.g., a Pearson's chi-squared test for discrete uniform distributions.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The distribution needs to be uniform only for table sizes that occur in the application.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] In particular, if one uses dynamic resizing with exact doubling and halving of the table size, then the hash function needs to be uniform only when the size is a power of two.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Here the index can be computed as some range of bits of the hash function.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] On the other hand, some hashing algorithms prefer to have the size be a prime number.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] For open addressing schemes, the hash function should also avoid *runs*, the mapping of two or more keys to consecutive slots.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Such runs may cause the lookup cost to skyrocket, even if the load factor is low and collisions are infrequent.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The popular multiplicative hash is claimed to have particularly poor run behavior.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] K-independent hashing offers a way to prove a certain hash function does not have bad keysets for a given type of hashtable.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] A number of K-independence results are known for collision resolution schemes such as linear probing and cuckoo hashing.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Since K-independence can prove a hash function works, one can then focus on finding the fastest possible such hash function.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] A search algorithm that uses hashing consists of two parts.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The first part is computing a hash function which transforms the search key into an array index.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The ideal case is such that no two search keys hash to the same array index.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] However, this is not always the case and impossible to guarantee for unseen given data.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Hence the second part of the algorithm is collision resolution.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The two common methods for collision resolution are separate chaining and open addressing.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] In separate chaining, the process involves building a linked list with key–value pair for each search array index.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The collided items are chained together through a single linked list, which can be traversed to access the item with a unique search key.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Collision resolution through chaining with linked list is a common method of implementation of hash tables.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] If the element is comparable either numerically or lexically, and inserted into the list by maintaining the total order, it results in faster termination of the unsuccessful searches.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] If the keys are ordered, it could be efficient to use "self-organizing" concepts such as using a self-balancing binary search tree, through which the theoretical worst case could be brought down to $O(\log {n})$ , although it introduces additional complexities.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] In dynamic perfect hashing, two-level hash tables are used to reduce the look-up complexity to be a guaranteed $O(1)$ in the worst case.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] In this technique, the buckets of k entries are organized as perfect hash tables with $k^{2}$ slots providing constant worst-case lookup time, and low amortized time for insertion.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] A study shows array-based separate chaining to be 97% more performant when compared to the standard linked list method under heavy load.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Techniques such as using fusion tree for each buckets also result in constant time for all operations with high probability.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The linked list of separate chaining implementation may not be cache-conscious due to spatial locality—locality of reference—when the nodes of the linked list are scattered across memory, thus the list traversal during insert and search may entail CPU cache inefficiencies.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Open addressing is another collision resolution technique in which every entry record is stored in the bucket array itself, and the hash resolution is performed through **probing**.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] When a new entry has to be inserted, the buckets are examined, starting with the hashed-to slot and proceeding in some *probe sequence*, until an unoccupied slot is found.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] When searching for an entry, the buckets are scanned in the same sequence, until either the target record is found, or an unused array slot is found, which indicates an unsuccessful search.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The performance of open addressing may be slower compared to separate chaining since the probe sequence increases when the load factor $\alpha$ approaches 1.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The probing results in an infinite loop if the load factor reaches 1, in the case of a completely filled table.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The average cost of linear probing depends on the hash function's ability to distribute the elements uniformly throughout the table to avoid runs, since formation of runs would result in increased search time.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Since the slots are located in successive locations, linear probing could lead to better utilization of CPU cache due to locality of references resulting in reduced memory latency.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Coalesced hashing is a hybrid of both separate chaining and open addressing in which the buckets or nodes link within the table.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The algorithm is ideally suited for fixed memory allocation.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The collision in coalesced hashing is resolved by identifying the largest-indexed empty slot on the hash table, then the colliding value is inserted into that slot.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The bucket is also linked to the inserted node's slot which contains its colliding hash address.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Cuckoo hashing is a form of open addressing collision resolution technique which guarantees $O(1)$ worst-case lookup complexity and constant amortized time for insertions.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The collision is resolved through maintaining two hash tables, each having its own hashing function, and collided slot gets replaced with the given item, and the preoccupied element of the slot gets displaced into the other hash table.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The process continues until every key has its own spot in the empty buckets of the tables; if the procedure enters into infinite loop—which is identified through maintaining a threshold loop counter—both hash tables get rehashed with newer hash functions and the procedure continues.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Hopscotch hashing is an open addressing based algorithm which combines the elements of cuckoo hashing, linear probing and chaining through the notion of a *neighbourhood* of buckets—the subsequent buckets around any given occupied bucket, also called a "virtual" bucket.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The algorithm is designed to deliver better performance when the load factor of the hash table grows beyond 90%; it also provides high throughput in concurrent settings, thus well suited for implementing resizable concurrent hash table.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Each bucket within the hash table includes an additional "hop-information"—an *H*-bit bit array for indicating the relative distance of the item which was originally hashed into the current virtual bucket within *H* − 1 entries.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] *H* − 1, subsequent swap and hop-info bit array manipulation of each bucket is performed in accordance with its neighbourhood invariant properties.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Robin Hood hashing is an open addressing based collision resolution algorithm; the collisions are resolved through favouring the displacement of the element that is farthest—or longest *probe sequence length* (PSL)—from its "home location" i.e. the bucket to which the item was hashed into.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] It is named after Robin Hood, a mythical heroic outlaw who stole from the rich to give to the poor.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Although Robin Hood hashing does not change the theoretical search cost, it significantly affects the variance of the distribution of the items on the buckets, i.e. dealing with long run formation in the hash table.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Each node within the hash table that uses Robin Hood hashing should be augmented to store an extra PSL value.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] If a hash table becomes "too empty" after deleting some elements, resizing may be performed to avoid excessive memory usage.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Generally, a new hash table with a size double that of the original hash table gets allocated privately and every item in the original hash table gets moved to the newly allocated one by computing the hash values of the items followed by the insertion operation.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Rehashing is simple, but computationally expensive.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Some hash table implementations, notably in real-time systems, cannot pay the price of enlarging the hash table all at once, because it may interrupt time-critical operations.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] If one cannot avoid dynamic resizing, a solution is to perform the resizing gradually to avoid storage blip—typically at 50% of new table's size—during rehashing and to avoid memory fragmentation that triggers heap compaction due to deallocation of large memory blocks caused by the old hash table.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] In such case, the rehashing operation is done incrementally through extending prior memory block allocated for the old hash table such that the buckets of the hash table remain unaltered.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] A common approach for amortized rehashing involves maintaining two hash functions $h_{\text{old}}$ and $h_{\text{new}}$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Linear hashing is an implementation of the hash table which enables dynamic growths or shrinks of the table one bucket at a time.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The performance of a hash table is dependent on the hash function's ability in generating quasi-random numbers ( $\sigma$ ) for entries in the hash table where K , n and $h(x)$ denotes the key, number of buckets and the hash function such that $\sigma \ =\ h(K)\ \%\ n$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] If the hash function generates the same $\sigma$ for distinct keys ( $K_{1}\neq K_{2},\ h(K_{1})\ =\ h(K_{2})$ ), this results in *collision*, which is dealt with in a variety of ways.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The constant time complexity ( $O(1)$ ) of the operation in a hash table is presupposed on the condition that the hash function doesn't generate colliding indices; thus, the performance of the hash table is directly proportional to the chosen hash function's ability to disperse the indices.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] However, construction of such a hash function is practically infeasible, that being so, implementations depend on case-specific collision resolution techniques in achieving higher performance.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] The best performance is obtained in the case that the hash function distributes the elements of the universe uniformaly, and the elements stored at the table are drawn at random from the universe.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] In this case, in hashing with chaining, the expected time for a successful search is ${\textstyle 1+{\frac {\alpha }{2}}+\Theta \left({\frac {1}{m}}\right)}$ , and the expected time for an unsuccessful search is ${\textstyle e^{-\alpha }+\alpha +\Theta \left({\frac {1}{m}}\right)}$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Hash tables are commonly used to implement many types of in-memory tables.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] They are used to implement associative arrays.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Hash tables may also be used as disk-based data structures and database indices (such as in dbm) although B-trees are more popular in these applications.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Hash tables can be used to implement caches, auxiliary data tables that are used to speed up the access to data that is primarily stored in slower media.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] In this application, hash collisions can be handled by discarding one of the two colliding entries—usually erasing the old item that is currently stored in the table and overwriting it with the new item, so every item in the table has a unique hash value.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Hash tables can be used in the implementation of set data structure, which can store unique values without any particular order; set is typically used in testing the membership of a value in the collection, rather than element retrieval.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] A transposition table to a complex Hash Table which stores information about each section that has been searched.
[src:open-addressing-probing/hash-table] Many programming languages provide hash table functionality, either as built-in associative arrays or as standard library modules.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Along with quadratic probing and double hashing, linear probing is a form of open addressing.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] In these schemes, each cell of a hash table stores a single key–value pair.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] When the hash function causes a collision by mapping a new key to a cell of the hash table that is already occupied by another key, linear probing searches the table for the closest following free location and inserts the new key there.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Lookups are performed in the same way, by searching the table sequentially starting at the position given by the hash function, until finding a cell with a matching key or an empty cell.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] It takes constant expected time per search, insertion, or deletion when implemented using a random hash function, a 5-independent hash function, or tabulation hashing.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Good results can also be achieved in practice with other hash functions such as MurmurHash.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Linear probing is a component of open addressing schemes for using a hash table to solve the dictionary problem.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] In the dictionary problem, a data structure should maintain a collection of key–value pairs subject to operations that insert or delete pairs from the collection or that search for the value associated with a given key.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] In open addressing solutions to this problem, the data structure is an array T (the hash table) whose cells *T*[*i*] (when nonempty) each store a single key–value pair.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] A hash function is used to map each key into the cell of T where that key should be stored, typically scrambling the keys so that keys with similar values are not placed near each other in the table.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] A hash collision occurs when the hash function maps a key into a cell that is already occupied by a different key.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Linear probing is a strategy for resolving collisions, by placing the new key into the closest following empty cell.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] To search for a given key x, the cells of T are examined, beginning with the cell at index *h*(*x*) (where h is the hash function) and continuing to the adjacent cells *h*(*x*) + 1, *h*(*x*) + 2, ..., until finding either an empty cell or a cell whose stored key is x.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] If a cell containing the key is found, the search returns the value from that cell.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Otherwise, if an empty cell is found, the key cannot be in the table, because it would have been placed in that cell in preference to any later cell that has not yet been searched.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] In this case, the search returns as its result that the key is not present in the dictionary.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] To insert a key–value pair (*x*,*v*) into the table (possibly replacing any existing pair with the same key), the insertion algorithm follows the same sequence of cells that would be followed for a search, until finding either an empty cell or a cell whose stored key is x.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] The new key–value pair is then placed into that cell.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] If the insertion would cause the load factor of the table (its fraction of occupied cells) to grow above some preset threshold, the whole table may be replaced by a new table, larger by a constant factor, with a new hash function, as in a dynamic array.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Setting this threshold close to zero and using a high growth rate for the table size leads to faster hash table operations but greater memory usage than threshold values close to one and low growth rates.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] A common choice would be to double the table size when the load factor would exceed 1/2, causing the load factor to stay between 1/4 and 1/2.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] It is also possible to remove a key–value pair from the dictionary.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] However, it is not sufficient to do so by simply emptying its cell.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] This would affect searches for other keys that have a hash value earlier than the emptied cell, but that are stored in a position later than the emptied cell.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] The emptied cell would cause those searches to incorrectly report that the key is not present.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Instead, when a cell i is emptied, it is necessary to search forward through the following cells of the table until finding either another empty cell or a key that can be moved to cell i (that is, a key whose hash value is equal to or earlier than i).
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] When an empty cell is found, then emptying cell i is safe and the deletion process terminates.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] But, when the search finds a key that can be moved to cell i, it performs this move.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] This has the effect of speeding up later searches for the moved key, but it also empties out another cell, later in the same block of occupied cells.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] The search for a movable key continues for the new emptied cell, in the same way, until it terminates by reaching a cell that was already empty.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] In this process of moving keys to earlier cells, each key is examined only once.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Therefore, the time to complete the whole process is proportional to the length of the block of occupied cells containing the deleted key, matching the running time of the other hash table operations.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Alternatively, it is possible to use a lazy deletion strategy in which a key–value pair is removed by replacing the value by a special flag value indicating a deleted key.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] However, these flag values will contribute to the load factor of the hash table.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] With this strategy, it may become necessary to clean the flag values out of the array and rehash all the remaining key–value pairs once too large a fraction of the array becomes occupied by deleted keys.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Linear probing provides good locality of reference, which causes it to require few uncached memory accesses per operation.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Because of this, for low to moderate load factors, it can provide very high performance.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] However, compared to some other open addressing strategies, its performance degrades more quickly at high load factors because of primary clustering, a tendency for one collision to cause more nearby collisions.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Additionally, achieving good performance with this method requires a higher-quality hash function than for some other collision resolution schemes.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Using linear probing, dictionary operations can be implemented in constant expected time.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] In other words, insert, remove and search operations can be implemented in O(1), as long as the load factor of the hash table is a constant strictly less than one.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] In more detail, the time for any particular operation (a search, insertion, or deletion) is proportional to the length of the contiguous block of occupied cells at which the operation starts.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] If all starting cells are equally likely, in a hash table with N cells, then a maximal block of k occupied cells will have probability *k*/*N* of containing the starting location of a search, and will take time *O*(*k*) whenever it is the starting location.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Therefore, the expected time for an operation can be calculated as the product of these two terms, *O*(*k*2/*N*), summed over all of the maximal blocks of contiguous cells in the table.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] This formula can be simplified by replacing Block(*i*,*k*) by a simpler necessary condition Full(*k*), the event that at least k elements have hash values that lie within a block of cells of length k.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] After this replacement, the value within the sum no longer depends on i, and the 1/*N* factor cancels the N terms of the outer summation.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] But by the multiplicative form of the Chernoff bound, when the load factor is bounded away from one, the probability that a block of length k contains at least k hashed values is exponentially small as a function of k, causing this sum to be bounded by a constant independent of n.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] It is also possible to perform the same analysis using Stirling's approximation instead of the Chernoff bound to estimate the probability that a block contains exactly k hashed values.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] In terms of the load factor α, the expected time to perform a successful search on a random key is *O*(1 + 1/(1 − *α*)), and the expected time to perform an unsuccessful search (or the insertion of a new key) is *O*(1 + 1/(1 − *α*)2).
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] For constant load factors, with high probability, the longest probe sequence (among the probe sequences for all keys stored in the table) has logarithmic length.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Linear probing hash tables suffer from a problem known as primary clustering, in which elements to group together into long contiguous runs.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] In terms of the load factor α, the expected length of the run containing a given element is $\Theta (1+1/(1-\alpha )^{2})$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] This is why insertions take time $\Theta (1+1/(1-\alpha )^{2})$ , as opposed to the running time of $\Theta (1+1/(1-\alpha ))$ achieved by other open-addressed hash tables such as uniform probing and double hashing.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Primary clustering also affects unsuccessful searches, since like insertions, they must travel to the end of a run.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Some variations of linear probing are able to achieve better bounds for unsuccessful searches and insertions, by using techniques that reduce primary clustering.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Because linear probing is especially sensitive to unevenly distributed hash values, it is important to combine it with a high-quality hash function that does not produce such irregularities.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] The analysis above assumes that each key's hash is a random number independent of the hashes of all the other keys.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] This assumption is unrealistic for most applications of hashing.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] However, random or pseudorandom hash values may be used when hashing objects by their identity rather than by their value.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] For instance, this is done using linear probing by the IdentityHashMap class of the Java collections framework.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] The hash value that this class associates with each object, its identityHashCode, is guaranteed to remain fixed for the lifetime of an object but is otherwise arbitrary.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Because the identityHashCode is constructed only once per object, and is not required to be related to the object's address or value, its construction may involve slower computations such as the call to a random or pseudorandom number generator.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] For instance, Java 8 uses an Xorshift pseudorandom number generator to construct these values.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] For most applications of hashing, it is necessary to compute the hash function for each value every time that it is hashed, rather than once when its object is created.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] In such applications, random or pseudorandom numbers cannot be used as hash values, because then different objects with the same value would have different hashes.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] And cryptographic hash functions (which are designed to be computationally indistinguishable from truly random functions) are usually too slow to be used in hash tables.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Instead, other methods for constructing hash functions have been devised.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] These methods compute the hash function quickly, and can be proven to work well with linear probing.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] In particular, linear probing has been analyzed from the framework of k-independent hashing, a class of hash functions that are initialized from a small random seed and that are equally likely to map any k-tuple of distinct keys to any k-tuple of indexes.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] The parameter k can be thought of as a measure of hash function quality: the larger k is, the more time it will take to compute the hash function but it will behave more similarly to completely random functions.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] For linear probing, 5-independence is enough to guarantee constant expected time per operation, while some 4-independent hash functions perform badly, taking up to logarithmic time per operation.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Another method of constructing hash functions with both high quality and practical speed is tabulation hashing.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] In this method, the hash value for a key is computed by using each byte of the key as an index into a table of random numbers (with a different table for each byte position).
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] The numbers from those table cells are then combined by a bitwise exclusive or operation.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Hash functions constructed this way are only 3-independent.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Nevertheless, linear probing using these hash functions takes constant expected time per operation.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Both tabulation hashing and standard methods for generating 5-independent hash functions are limited to keys that have a fixed number of bits.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] To handle strings or other types of variable-length keys, it is possible to compose a simpler universal hashing technique that maps the keys to intermediate values and a higher quality (5-independent or tabulation) hash function that maps the intermediate values to hash table indices.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] They point out that each table look-up require several cycles, being more expensive than simple arithmetic operations.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] They also found MurmurHash to be superior than tabulation hashing: "By studying the results provided by Mult and Murmur, we think that the trade-off for by tabulation (...) is less attractive in practice".
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] The idea of an associative array that allows data to be accessed by its value rather than by its address dates back to the mid-1940s in the work of Konrad Zuse and Vannevar Bush, but hash tables were not described until 1953, in an IBM memorandum by Hans Peter Luhn.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Luhn used a different collision resolution method, chaining, rather than linear probing.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Knuth (1963) summarizes the early history of linear probing.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] It was the first open addressing method, and was originally synonymous with open addressing.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] According to Knuth, it was first used by Gene Amdahl, Elaine M.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] McGraw (née Boehme), and Arthur Samuel in 1954, in an assembler program for the IBM 701 computer.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] The first published description of linear probing is by Peterson (1957), who also credits Samuel, Amdahl, and Boehme but adds that "the system is so natural, that it very likely may have been conceived independently by others either before or since that time".
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Another early publication of this method was by Soviet researcher Andrey Ershov, in 1958.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] The first theoretical analysis of linear probing, showing that it takes constant expected time per operation with random hash functions, was given by Knuth.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Sedgewick calls Knuth's work "a landmark in the analysis of algorithms".
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Knuth's original analysis was never formally published, and the first published analysis was due to Konheim and Weiss in 1966.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Knuth's analysis disproved an earlier conjecture by Peterson that, at load factor $\alpha =1-\varepsilon$ , the expected time per insertion should be $\Theta (1+\varepsilon ^{-1})$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Knuth showed instead that the time per operation grows as at a rate of $\Theta (1+\varepsilon ^{-2})$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] This effect, in which the insertion time grows quadratically faster than one might intuitively guess, became known as primary clustering.
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Subsequent work has introduced several algorithmic techniques to reduce primary clustering, including a variation of linear probing known as graveyard hashing that achieves the ideal bound of $\Theta (1+\varepsilon ^{-1})$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/linear-probing] Other later developments include a more detailed analysis of the probability distribution of the running time, amortized analyses for workloads with both insertions and deletions, and analyses of linear probing using explicit families of hash functions.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] in which the interval between probes is fixed — often set to 1.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] The main trade offs between these methods are that linear probing has the best cache performance but is most sensitive to clustering, while double hashing has poor cache performance but exhibits virtually no clustering; quadratic probing falls in between in both areas.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] Double hashing can also require more computation than other forms of probing.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] Some open addressing methods, such as Hopscotch hashing, Robin Hood hashing, last-come-first-served hashing and cuckoo hashing move existing keys around in the array to make room for the new key.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] This gives better maximum search times than the methods based on probing.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] A critical influence on performance of an open addressing hash table is the *load factor*; that is, the proportion of the slots in the array that are used.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] As the load factor increases towards 100%, the number of probes that may be required to find or insert a given key rises dramatically.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] Once the table becomes full, probing algorithms may even fail to terminate.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] Even with good hash functions, load factors are normally limited to 80%.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] A poor hash function can exhibit poor performance even at very low load factors by generating significant clustering, especially with the simplest linear addressing method.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] Generally typical load factors with most open addressing methods are 50%, while separate chaining typically can use up to 100%.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] The following pseudocode is an implementation of an open addressing hash table with linear probing and single-slot stepping, a common approach that is effective if the hash function is good.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] Each of the **lookup**, **set** and **remove** functions use a common internal function **find_slot** to locate the array slot that either does or should contain a given key.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] operation to insert all the elements of the old array into the new larger array.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] , for example by doubling the old array size.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] For all records in a cluster, there must be no vacant slots between their natural hash position and their current position (else lookups will terminate before finding the record).
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] is a vacant slot that might be invalidating this property for subsequent records in the cluster.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] would naturally land in the hash table if there were no collisions.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] Another technique for removal is simply to mark the slot as deleted.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] However this eventually requires rebuilding the table simply to remove deleted records.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] The methods above provide *O*(1) updating and removal of existing records, with occasional rebuilding if the high-water mark of the table size grows.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] The *O*(1) remove method above is only possible in linearly probed hash tables with single-slot stepping.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] In the case where many records are to be deleted in one operation, marking the slots for deletion and later rebuilding may be more efficient.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] Here *n* is the number of elements in the table, *m* the table size, $\alpha =n/m$ the load factor, $U_{n}$ the number of probes in an unsuccessful search and $S_{n}$ the number of probes in a successful search.
[src:open-addressing-probing/open-addressing] Note that the expectation deteriorates to infinity when the load factor approaches 1.
[src:open-addressing-probing/quadratic-probing] Quadratic probing is often recommended as an alternative to linear probing because it incurs less clustering.
[src:open-addressing-probing/quadratic-probing] Quadratic probing exhibits better locality of reference than many other hash table such as chaining; however, for queries, quadratic probing does not have as good locality as linear probing, causing the latter to be faster in some settings.
[src:open-addressing-probing/quadratic-probing] Quadratic probing was first introduced by Ward Douglas Maurer in 1968.
[src:open-addressing-probing/quadratic-probing] Several subsequent variations of the data structure were proposed in the 1970s in order to guarantee that the probe sequence hits every slot without cycling prematurely.
[src:open-addressing-probing/quadratic-probing] Quadratic probing is widely believed to avoid the clustering effects that make linear probing slow at high load factors.
[src:open-addressing-probing/quadratic-probing] It serves as the basis for many widely used high-performance hash-tables, including Google's open-source Abseil hash table.
[src:open-addressing-probing/quadratic-probing] It is conjectured that quadratic probing, when filled to $1-\epsilon$ full, supports insertions in expected time $O(\epsilon ^{-1})$ .
[src:open-addressing-probing/quadratic-probing] Proving this, or even proving *any* non-trivial time bound for quadratic probing remains open.
[src:open-addressing-probing/quadratic-probing] The closest result, due to Kuszmaul and Xi, shows that, at load factors of less than $\approx 0.089$ , insertions take $O(1)$ expected time.
[src:open-addressing-probing/quadratic-probing] Let *h*(*k*) be a hash function that maps an element *k* to an integer in [0, *m*−1], where *m* is the size of the table.
[src:open-addressing-probing/quadratic-probing] For a given hash table, the values of *c*1 and *c*2 remain constant.
[src:open-addressing-probing/quadratic-probing] If the sign of the offset is alternated (e.g. +1, −4, +9, −16, etc.), and if the number of buckets is a prime number p congruent to 3 modulo 4 (e.g.
[src:open-addressing-probing/quadratic-probing] 3, 7, 11, 19, 23, 31, etc.), then the first p offsets will be unique (modulo p ).
[src:open-addressing-probing/quadratic-probing] In other words, a permutation of 0 through $p-1$ is obtained, and, consequently, a free bucket will always be found as long as at least one exists.
